<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sainovic Views Economic Recovery, Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sainovic Views Economic Recovery, Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0805165294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1639 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0805165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 8 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Deputy Prime 
Minister Nikola Sainovic said on Sunday the success of the 
country's economic recovery programme was a heavy blow to 
international sanctions against it. The sanctions were 
originally introduced to cause an economic collapse in 
Yugoslavia, but the programme has prevented this and in this way 
made senseless the very purpose of the sanctions, Sainovic told 
the local radio in Kragujevac. 
  In late May of 1992, the U.N. Security Council introduced 
tough sanctions against Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro) for its 
alleged involvement in civil war in neighbouring 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Those who imposed the blockade now see that 
the Yugoslav economy is recovering and that the sanctions are 
also affecting the countries neighbouring on Yugoslavia which 
are allegedly supported by the big powers, said Sainovic. 
  "The positive results of the programme have become evident 
in 
the first 100 days of its implementation, primarily as concerns 
the curbing of hyperinflation and revival of production." The 
basic goal now is to sustain production growth and ensure 
revival of the overall economic activity, explained Sainovic. 
  The economic recovery programme, which was launched on 
January 24, slashed inflation to zero. Before the programme was 
introduced, the monthly inflation in Yugoslavia soared to the 
unbelievable 310 million percent. One of the effects of the 
sanctions was a sharp drop in industrial production which was 
reversed after the programme was introduced. In February, 
industrial output rose by 12.4 percent on the January figure and 
in March by 21.3 percent. 
  The architect of the Yugoslav economic recovery programme is 
Dr. Dragoslav Avramovic, 77, who for decades worked with the 
World Bank and other U.N. specialized agencies. Dr. Avramovic is 
currently governor of the National Bank of Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

