<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Announces Trial of French Aid Workers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Announces Trial of French Aid Workers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0605193094 Paris AFP in English 1904 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0605193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, May 6 (AFP) -- Eleven French aid workers 
held by the Bosnian Serbs for a month are to go on trial next 
week accused of arms smuggling on behalf of the mainly Moslem 
Bosniam army, Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic said Friday 
[6 May]. Karadzic told a French official at the Bosnian Serb 
headquarters in Pale near Sarajevo the 11 would be tried 
together, according to a French source. (In Paris, the French 
foreign ministry confirmed the meeting with Karadzic and again 
called for the volunteer workers' release.) 
  The Serbs had earlier indicated only three of the men with 
the non-governmental organisation Premiere Urgence (First Aid) 
would face trial on Sunday while the other eight would be 
released. The 11 are being held near the Serb barracks at 
Lukavica, an important Serb military base just five kilometres 
(three miles) outside the Bosnian capital. French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe has said the aid workers are the victims of 
Serb "manipulation" and described the 11 as "hostages." Paris 
has sent foreign ministry secretary general Bertrand Dufourcq to 
Belgrade to demand the workers be released, as it believes the 
Serbian government could hold the key to their fate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

