<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croat Commander Threatens Brcko Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Croat Commander Threatens Brcko Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0705131594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1233 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0705131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Brcko, May 7 (TANJUG) -- Commander of the Bosnian 
Croat Army in northern Bosnia-Herzegovina confirmed on Saturday 
[7 May] that joint Moslem-Croat forces were preparing an attack 
on the Serb corridor in the north of this former Yugoslav 
republic. 
  "The Serb corridor through (the region of) Posavina must not 
exist and its capture is the only objective of Croats and 
Moslems," Djuro Matuzovic, Bosnian Croat force commander for the 
area of orasje in northern Bosnia-Herzegovina, told the local 
Croatian radio. "If this is not resolved politically, we 
soldiers expect an order which we shall carry out," Matuzovic 
threatened. 
  Bosnian Moslems and Croats have lately been concentrating 
strong forces towards the Serb town of Brcko which is situated 
in the narrowest part of the corridor which links eastern and 
western parts of the Bosnian Serb Republic. This was confirmed 
on Friday also by two members of the 108th Brigade of the 
Bosnian Croat Army, the so-called Croatian Defence Council HVO, 
which is deployed in the Posavina region. The two soldiers 
deserted and surrendered to Serb units with the explanation that 
they did not wish to take part in the upcoming attack on Serbs. 
  Serb military sources said in Brcko on Saturday that the 
Croat soldiers also gave a series of facts which prove that 
preparations for a Moslem-Croat offensive in the region of 
Posavina were proceeding unabated. According to these men, 
machinery and equipment have been massively mobilized from 
private enterpreneurs in order to step up the preparations for 
the offensive. 
  Bosnian Moslem Army Commander Rasim Delic also said on May 2 
that units under his command were preparing an offensive on 
Brcko in order to cut through the Serb corridor. The Serb side 
has reached agreement with representatives of the U.N. 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) on the deployment of U.N. observers 
in the area of Brcko and offered a truce in that region which it 
said its forces would carry out unilaterally even if the Moslems 
refused to accept it. 
  Moslems on Friday called off talks between military 
commanders of Bosnian Moslem and Serb forces on a cease-fire on 
the Brcko front, which had been scheduled for Saturday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

