<H3> <TI>   Muslims Cancel Meeting on Brcko Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Cancel Meeting on Brcko Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605201894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1946 GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0605201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 6 May (TANJUG) -- The Muslim Government 
has cancelled the meeting between the commander of the 2d 
(Tuzla) Corps of the Muslim forces and the commander of the 
eastern Bosnian corps of the republic of Srpska army, scheduled 
for tomorrow -- the information service of the main headquarters 
of the republic of Srpska army announced this evening. 
According to a statement by the information service, Colonel 
Engelen, the chief of staff of the UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Forces] command for the northeast, who mediated in the 
organization of the meeting, today sent the following letter to 
Major General Novica Simic, the commander of the eastern Bosnian 
corps of the republic of Srpska army: 
  ``1. Although General Hazim Sadic, commander of the 2d Corps 
of the Bosnian Army, wants to meet you as soon as possible, his 
government has ordered him to cancel his earlier acceptance of 
the meeting. This will be dealt with at the highest level. 
  "2. This is why we suggest that the meeting scheduled for 
1300 on 7 May be postponed until further notice." 
  The information service statement, also forwarded to TANJUG, 
says that "this latest refusal to negotiate on the part of the 
extremist Muslim leaders in Sarajevo clearly shows that they are 
in favor of the war option, that they want to procrastinate with 
the negotiations as long as possible, and that they will not 
give up on the planned and prepared offensive against the town 
of Brcko and Serbian Posavina." 
  As Gen. Simic told TANJUG today, the talks were to focus on 
a 
cease-fire on the Brcko battlefield, exchange of prisoners, the 
unhindered passage of civilians, and the establishment of the 
so-called hot line. 

</TEXT>

