<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Resolution `Dead Letter' in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Resolution `Dead Letter' in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905110694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1000 GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0905110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mustafa Kurtovic from Gorazde] </F>
  [Text] The UN resolution and the NATO ultimatum represent 
only a dead letter on the paper and the flagrant deceit by the 
international community that the civilian population of the free 
territory of Gorazde will be protected. Nothing contained in 
the decisions adopted by the Security Council and NATO has been 
respected in the free territory of Gorazde. A real hell reigns 
here. Is indeed a pity that reputable world press and 
television agencies have not come here to film the suffering of 
the unarmed people. 
  The attempts by the citizens from local communities and the 
villages of Kopaci, Uvjeri, Vran Potok, Causevici, Kazlagici, 
Zubcici, Zuzevo, Milanovici, Brijez, Pticino Polje, and other 
areas in the 3 km zone to return to their houses have all been 
in vain. 
  The evacuation of the seriously wounded children has not 
been 
going according to plan either. We do not know whose mistake it 
was, but a three-year-old boy, Adnan Azovic, was not on the list 
of those evacuated to a modern hospital. He is seriously ill. 
Permission for his evacuation was obtained a year ago and yet 
he is still in Gorazde. His parents have medicines, [name 
indistinct] for only two more days. This medicine means life to 
him. If he is not evacuated, his childhood will end forever. 
Therefore, we again appeal to UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] and 
all international medical organizations to secure the evacuation 
of the seriously ill children from Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

