<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yugoslavia's Simic Meets Officials in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yugoslavia's Simic Meets Officials in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0605211594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2035 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0605211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, May 6 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Deputy Prime 
Minister Zeljko Simic said on Friday U.N. special envoy for 
former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi had confirmed his principled 
stand that only peace for all of Bosnia-Herzegovina could 
provide a sound foundation for a sensible and lasting political 
settlement. In a statement to TANJUG, Simic said Akashi had 
told him on the telephone he would continue to insist on 
neutrality in the Bosnian civil war and non-use of force in 
dealing with the problem. 
  Simic, who attended the sixth session of the working group 
for economic issues of the Geneva-based international conference 
on the former Yugoslavia, on Friday met with conference 
co-chairman Thorvald Stoltenberg, Akashi's closest aides, 
several influential international figures and representatives of 
international institutions. Among others he met with the 
director of the International Migration Service, with whom he 
had what he described as a cordial and constructive meeting 
which focused on a draft agreement on regulating the status of 
the organization's Belgrade office. 
  During the meeting, Simic spoke of the intention of some 
West 
European countries to launch a coordinated action of 
repatriation of Yugoslavs, mostly ethnic Albanians from the 
Serbian province of Kosovo-Metohija. The Yugoslav official also 
met with Croatian ambassador in Geneva Miomir Zuzula, with whom 
he discussed normalization of bilateral relations. 
  Simic described the sixth session of the economic group as 
unsuccessful and dismissed as unfeasible a proposal put forth by 
chairman Jean Durrieu for reviving and reconstructing the 
economic space of former Yugoslavia. This goal is unattainable 
for as long as the civil war in Bosnia rages on and sanctions 
against Yugoslavia are in force, he explained. 
  Later on Friday, Simic is due to meet with the other 
co-chairman of the international conference on the former 
Yugoslavia, Lord Owen, and the president of the World Health 
Organization. He may also meet with U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali before returning to Yugoslavia later tonight. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

