<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7 Leaders Meet in Warsaw, Discuss Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-7 Leaders Meet in Warsaw, Discuss Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata, Rexrodt on Numerical Targets </H4>

<F P=102> OW0705100594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0933 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0705100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 7 KYODO -- Japanese International Trade 
and Industry Minister Eijiro Hata said Saturday [7 May] that 
Japan will send a trade expert to the former East Germany to 
help promote exports from the region. Meeting with his German 
counterpart Guenter Rexrodt, Hata said the expert from the 
semigovernmental Japan External Trade Organization will look 
into possible export products in the region for a year, a 
Japanese official said. Rexrodt told Hata that the former East 
Germany needs foreign assistance and he expects the Japanese 
trade expert to bring good results, the official said. 
  Touching on stalled Japan-U.S. talks on a new trade 
framework, Hata reiterated Japan's opposition to U.S. demands 
that Tokyo set numerical targets to measure progress in reducing 
Japan's trade surplus with the United States. 
  Rexrodt said there must be progress in opening Japan's 
markets, but noted that he opposes setting numerical targets as 
sought by the U.S. as Japan does. Hata and Rexrodt are in the 
Polish capital to attend the third meeting of economic officials 
from the Group of Seven (G-7) industrial nations and from 
officials from Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union on 
East-West trade issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55016 </DOCNO>
