<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   G-7 Leaders Meet in Warsaw, Discuss Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    G-7 Leaders Meet in Warsaw, Discuss Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Market Transition Discussed </H4>

<F P=102> OW0705143094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1414 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0705143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, May 7 KYODO -- A two-day East-West economic 
and trade conference was set to close Saturday [7 May] after 
adopting a statement summarizing its discussions on cooperation 
to promote the transition of the former Soviet Union and its 
East European allies to market economies. 
  Discussions in the final-day session centered on government 
policies to promote economic reforms in the region and measures 
to close regional economic gaps, conference sources said. The 
participants also exchanged views on a declaration, adopted by 
business executives at a business forum Friday, calling for 200 
billion dollars of direct foreign investment in the region by 
the year 2000, they said. 
  Present at the discussions on Saturday morning were 
ministers 
in charge of economic, industrial and trade affairs and business 
representatives from the Group of Seven (G-7) major 
industrialized nations and 10 countries of Eastern Europe and 
former Soviet republics, they said. The declaration also called 
for the privatization of state-run enterprises in the 10 
countries and promotion of East-West trade, they said. 
  Eijiro Hata, Japan's minister of international trade and 
industry, told a ministerial-level session in the afternoon that 
Japan will cooperate to promote industrial development in the 
region. In connection with this, Hata said Tokyo will hold 
seminars in Moscow and Warsaw in late September to help promote 
the development of smaller enterprises, foreign trade and 
investment. Hata also said Japan will conduct surveys in two 
former East-bloc countries, including Poland, in 1994 and 1995 
to work out measures to overcome the economic recession. 
  The United States is likely to be selected as the site for 
the next session in 1995, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55018 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu089aa_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
