<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Martic Rejects Krajina Integration With Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martic Rejects Krajina Integration With Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0805165994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1338 GMT 8 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0805165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Kragujevac, 8 May (TANJUG) -- The Serbian people 
will on no account allow any threats to the territorial link 
between the Serb lands, despite our lasting commitment to peace 
and a political solution, Milan Martic, president of the 
republic of Serb Krajina, told "The Hallmark of the Times" 
program of Kragujevac radio. [passage omitted] 
  Asked why the talks between the republic of Serb Krajina and 
Croatia had been delayed and when they will resume, Martic said: 
"This is not up to us. We insist that the talks take place at a 
neutral venue and on equal footing for both sides. The 
condition for continuing the talks is the removal of Paragraph 
12 of the UN Security Council Resolution 820, relating to 
exports and imports. Making any concessions to Croatia, even 
when it comes to transport links, is out of the question unless 
we are treated equally. Gaining transport links would mean 
nothing to us if we cannot export or import goods, and for that 
it is necessary to remove Resolution 820." 
  Asked to comment on the increasingly frequent statements by 
western and Croatian politicians about the reintegration of the 
republic of Serb Krajina into Croatia, with a high degree of 
autonomy, Martic said: "These are merely their wishes." He 
added: "We are convinced we are fighting for the survival of the 
Serb people and we will persist in it to the very end." 
  "We will not give in on our basic demand -- the right to 
self- determination of our people, as guaranteed to all other 
peoples in the world." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55026 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu089_i_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Sends Protest Note About Akashi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic Sends Protest Note About Akashi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0605184794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0605184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dear listeners: We have just received a copy of 
the letter thatAlija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, has sent to UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali. 
  Mr. Secretary General: Your envoy for Yugoslavia, Mr. 
Yasushi Akashi, has, with his latest actions, destroyed the 
minimum of trust that is a precondition for any kind of 
cooperation. Our people and the international public have for a 
long time been witness to his strange and incomprehensible 
techniques in handling the basic issues of war or peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. In our view, his conduct and decisions 
regarding the crisis in Gorazde are clearly contrary to the 
corresponding Security Council resolutions and NATO decisions. 
They have helped the aggressor to maintain his machine for 
killing people and destroying cities. In granting permission to 
Karadzic's Serbs yesterday to allow the passage of tanks through 
the zone strictly forbidden for heavy arms, and securing an 
escort for these tanks to be moved to new positions, Mr. Akashi 
has effectively sided with the aggressor. I am sure that no 
well-intentioned person, including his closest associates, can 
understand or explain Mr. Akashi's conduct. It is no wonder 
that the Serbs are ignoring the decisions of the international 
community if its official representatives fail to observe them. 
The result of such conduct is an endless continuation of the 
war, which has entered its third year in this region, and an 
increasing remoteness of any chances for peace. 
  Mr. Secretary General, it is my duty to inform you that 
these 
reasons make it impossible for the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government 
to continue to cooperate with Mr. Akashi. 
  Respectfully yours, Alija Izetbegovic 

</TEXT>

