<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seek Broadest Coalition Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seek Broadest Coalition Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005113994 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1005113994 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to Imre Szekeres, executive deputy 
chairman of the Hungarian Socialist Party [MSZP], if the MSZP 
wins the elections, the return of the nomenclature which existed 
four years ago is out of the question. Szekeres, speaking on 
the "Sunrise" program on Hungarian television, confirmed that 
even if the MSZP obtains the absolute majority of the votes, it 
would consider it necessary to have the broadest possible 
coalition government. Although many expect it, the MSZP does 
not intend to bring the Christian Democratic People's Party 
[KDNP] into the government. The reason for this is the KDNP's 
performance over the past four years. 
  Imre Szekeres and Ivan Petoe, chairman of the Alliance of 
Free Democrats, who also participated in the TV program, both 
agreed that the tone of the elections ought not to change in the 
second round. In their view, the voters should concentrate on 
the individual candidates of the parties, and it would be 
desirable if these candidates could have an opportunity to 
introduce themselves to the electorate on Channel 1 of Hungarian 
Television, and not only on cable television. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

