<F P=103> LD0905210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The third day of negotiations on the implementation 
of the Washington agreement between the Croats and Bosniaks 
ended at the U.S. Embassy with the exchange of maps. Tihomir 
Vinkovic reports from Vienna: 
  [Vinkovic] The negotiations lasted a long time, and some 
progress was made after all. The questions of external borders 
with the Serbs, and of the leaderhip of the federation and the 
government have been been resolved in principle. The question 
that remains to be resolved is the number of the cantons in the 
federation and their borders. The maps were drafted and 
exchanged at the end of today's round of talks. The delegation 
of the Bosnian Croats, led by Kresimir Zubak, exchanged the 
delineation maps with the Bosniak delegation, led by Haris 
Silajdzic. 
  The contentious areas are central Bosnia and the 
municipalities of Mostar and Stolac. The positions on central 
Bosnia have converged, Kresimir Zubak said. But is this enough 
to reach an agreement? 
  The part of the negotiations dealing with the relations 
between the Bosniak-Croat federation and the Republic of Croatia 
passed without difficulties. Croatian Foreign Minister Mate 
Granic took part in it. 
  The only certain thing is that the negotiations will 
continue 
tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

