<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Republic Gains WEU Associate Partner Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Republic Gains WEU Associate Partner Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0905173994 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0905173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Czech Republic gained associate 
partner status in the West European Union [WEU] today. This took 
place at a session of a WEU consultative forum which was 
attended by Foreign Affairs Minister Josef Zieleniec and Defense 
Minister Antonin Baudys. Our special correspondent Klara 
Stejskalova reports from Luxembourg: 
  [Stejskalova] The WEU is the only European organization with 
authority on security questions. It brings together 10 
countries of the European Twelve. The countries of eastern and 
central Europe -- that is, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Bulgaria, 
Romania, and the three Baltic republics, apart from the Czech 
Republic -- have so far had observer status only. Associate 
partner status means, according to Jozef Zieleniec, that our 
contact with the WEU will cease to be diplomatic and will become 
a working one. This means that we are becoming more and more a 
part of the mechanism of European integration. He said the WEU 
will now become an organization that will gradually take over 
the role of security guarantor in Europe. 
  Today can be marked as significant. At last we can 
participate, by our vote, in formulating various aspects of 
policy; for example, a center for planning European identity has 
been formed, among other things. [passage omitted] 
  On the other hand one has to admit that the associate 
countries can take part in discussions, but cannot block 
decisions. Associate status is thus, to some extent, a mere 
formality which certainly does not mean an increase in our 
security. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

