<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities May Deny Visa to Zhirinovskiy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Authorities May Deny Visa to Zhirinovskiy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1005111794 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1005111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "No Entry in Macedonia for </F>
Zhirinovskiy"] 
  [Text] Radio Belgrade reports that the president of the 
Democratic Association of Serbs in Macedonia, Bora Ristic, has 
invited the leader of the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia, 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy (presently visiting Belgrade), to visit 
the Serbs in "The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia 
[FYROM]." In his interview for Radio Skopje, Ristic said 
"Zhirinovskiy's behavior is quite interesting, some even say 
extreme. As he is visiting Yugoslavia at the moment, we invited 
him as an ordinary citizen, to get directly acquainted with his 
philosophy and views on the Balkan region. But, I believe 
chances are he will not be able to come, as the Bolsheviks in 
Belgrade, and I do not think these Bolsheviks in Macedonia are 
any better, have deprived him of the right to publicly appear in 
Belgrade." 
  Radio Skopje unofficially informs that the Macedonian 
authorities are not inclined to grant Zhirinovskiy entry and 
stay in the country. The A1 television finds out Zhirinovskiy 
had planned to arrive in Macedonia at the Skopje airport. The 
airport authorities were allegedly ordered not to allow 
Zhirinovskiy to set foot on Macedonia territory. A1 reports 
that the air companies have also brought a decision not to allow 
Zhirinovskiy to board any of their planes flying on 
international routes. 

</TEXT>

