<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stability Issued Debated </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stability Issued Debated </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0605202594 Prague CTK in English 1658 GMT 6 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0605202594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 6 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic and 
Britain agree that the question of stability of Central and 
Eastern Europe is important for the continent, but differ in the 
accent on what is the cause and what is the consequence, Czech 
Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec told CTK today. He was 
referring to his talks with British Foreign Secretary Douglas 
Hurd earlier today during which the European security and 
stability pact was also taken up. 
  An international conference on the pact will be held in 
Paris 
at the end of May. The pact, proposed by French Premier Edouard 
Balladur last June, is to ensure stability and security in 
Europe, protect economic and trade interests, and result in the 
conclusion of agreements on good neighborhood and respect for 
the rights of ethnic minorities. 
  Zieleniec said all European countries, including the Czech 
Republic, espoused the goals set by the European Union (EU) -- 
finding a way of making Central and Eastern Europe a genuine 
part of the continent and gradually integrating it into the EU. 
  He stressed that views on ways of achieving these goals were 
not always entirely identical. The Czech Republic stresses the 
Western experience that the problems of ethnic minorities are 
best solved within a democratic and law-abiding state which has 
a well functioning economy based on private ownership. 
  Zieleniec said it was very difficult to treat the minority 
issue as an isolated one in a multilateral international 
agreement, without stressing the need for democracy and a 
law-abiding state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

