<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec Views WEU Associate Membership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zieleniec Views WEU Associate Membership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905192094 Prague CTK in English 1831 GMT 9 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0905192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luxembourg, May 9 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic and 
eight other Central and Eastern European countries were today 
granted associate membership of the Western European Union 
(WEU). This allows the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, 
Poland, Bulgaria, Romania, Lithuania, Estonia, and Latvia access 
to the regular twice monthly WEU delegates' meetings in Brussels 
and to send soldiers to peace keeping operations, but does not 
give them security guarantees or the right of veto. 
  The Czech Republic was represented at today's ceremony by 
Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec and Defense Minister Antonin 
Baudys. At the meeting Zieleniec said he welcomed the fact that 
after the NATO summit (at which the Partnership for Peace 
project was approved) the WEU had come up with an initiative 
that would bring the Czech Republic closer to the process of 
building an European defense identity. The Czech Republic felt 
the same responsibility for the safety of the continent as the 
West did, he added. 
  He later told journalists that from now on contacts with the 
WEU would stop being merely diplomatic and would take on a 
working character. The WEU was gradually changing into the 
military pillar of Europe, Zieleniec said. 
  After the ceremony Zieleniec met his French counterpart 
Alain 
Juppe. They exchanged views on the preparation for the 
forthcoming meeting on the proposed stability pact in Paris, 
agreeing that it was vitally important that the meeting should 
take place and produce positive results for European security. 

</TEXT>

