<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Announces Rejection of Security Bill </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Announces Rejection of Security Bill </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0505150194 Prague CTK in English 1310 GMT 5 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0505150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, May 5 (CTK) -- There will not be any new 
law on national security, Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus told 
journalists today. He was speaking after today's meeting of 
cabinet ministers rejected a draft bill on national security 
presented by Defense Minister Antonin Baudys. The draft was 
drawn up in the radical post-revolutionary spirit and it aimed 
to completely overhaul the existing legislation, Klaus said. 
  The ministers retained the existing law except for a few 
minor changes in the wording, concerning the threat to people's 
security and the extension of the powers of authorities. They 
agreed that no new bodies should be set up in the security 
sector. The bill concerned the deployment of the army for 
life-saving operations necessitated by natural disasters or 
nuclear power plant emergencies. 
  Rules governing the deployment of emergency services 
including the army and fire and security services in the event 
of large-scale disasters, and rules governing the duties of 
individuals in case of national emergencies are at present 
scattered among several laws. The draft bill aimed to bring the 
matter under a single heading. 

</TEXT>

