<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Reaffirms ODS Position on Senate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Klaus Reaffirms ODS Position on Senate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0805173494 Prague CTK in English 1455 GMT 7 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0805173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Teplice nad Becvou, North Moravia, May 7 (CTK) -- 
Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus said today the Executive Council of 
his Civic Democratic Party (ODS) had reaffirmed that the ODS 
stuck to 81 "clear, transparent and comprehensible" 
constituencies for Senate elections. Speaking during a pause in 
the council's deliberations, Klaus said the council "is afraid 
of creating complex electoral systems existing at one place 
somewhere in the world" and was resolutely opposed to it. 
  The ODS Executive Council has recommended to create a 
comprehensible, clear system providing for one-round voting if 
possible, in which the winner of the biggest number of votes 
would be elected senator, Klaus said. He allowed for the 
two-round variant. 
  The other three coalition parties, the Civic Democratic 
Alliance (ODA), the Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak 
People's Party (KDU-CSL) and the Christian Democratic Party 
(KDS), had favoured the creation of 27 "three-mandate" 
districts, each of which would send three senators to the new 
house. 
  After a meeting of the four parties' chairmen last week, 
Klaus said the parties were now inclining to the opinion that 
elections to the as yet unformed Senate should take place in 81 
one-mandate constitutions in a direct majority system. 
  Klaus said today the Executive Council would not order party 
leaders to "run for the Senate at any cost if they prefer 
running for the Chamber of Deputies two years later." He called 
the chamber a much more important instrument of the Czech 
Republic's parliamentary system. 
  The Senate elections will probably be held in the autumn, 
when also local elections are slated to be held. Elections to 
the Chamber of Deputies are to be held in 1996. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

