<H3> <TI>   ODS Wants Proportional System in Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ODS Wants Proportional System in Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0705145094 Prague CTK in English 1926 GMT 6 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0705145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Teplice nad Becvou, north Moravia, May 6 (CTK) -- 
The Civic Democratic Party (ODS) would continue its effort to 
cut the number of members in local representative bodies by 
one-third to one-half and to apply the proportional system in 
local elections, spokeswoman Jana Petrova said today. Speaking 
after a session of the ODS Executive Council, she said: "We are 
afraid that our deputies' group will be one of the few to be 
asserting the system because it is not advantageous for small 
parties." Local elections are to take place in November. 
  Petrova said that the working principles of the ODS election 
program had been drafted. The party will turn to the 
independent candidates who are famous personalities in 
particular communities because independents' participation in 
politics was "beneficial," she added. "Presently we are 
selecting an agency for local elections because good candidates 
having a good program must be sold well," Petrova said. 
  The ODS is the strongest parliamentary party with 66 out of 
a 
total of 200 seats. Its chairman is Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus. 

</TEXT>

