  [Text] Budapest, 9 May (MTI) -- The Independent 
Smallholders' Party (FKGP) has emerged from the elections 
stronger and legitimised, party chairman Jozsef Torgyan told a 
press conference on Monday. 
  While the FKGP is gravely concerned by the socialist-liberal 
victory in the elections, they see the results as the sovereign 
choice of the Hungarian people, and are preparing for a 
contructive opposition role. Torgyan believes the Smallholders 
will lead the national Christian grouping in the new Parliament. 
On their results so far, 8.8 per cent of the votes, the FKGP 
think they might win 40-45 mandates out of the 386. 

