<H3> <TI>   SZDSZ's Kuncze on Second Round of Voting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SZDSZ's Kuncze on Second Round of Voting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905165894 Budapest MTI in English 1616 GMT 9 May 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0905165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 9 May (MTI) -- One million plus votes 
cast for the Alliance of Free Democrats (SZDSZ) prove the party 
has a stable voter base, and that Hungarian politics is 
three-cornered now: The right is split but still led by the 
Hungarian Democratic Forum (MDF), the left is the Socialists, 
leaving the Free Democrats in the middle, Gabor Kuncze, SZDSZ 
prime minister candidate, told reporters today. What will be at 
stake in the second round will be the Socialists' ability to win 
an absolute majority in Parliament, something which the Free 
Democrats see as undesirable, Kuncze said. He was happy to see 
extremists squeezed out of Parliament. 
  SZDSZ Chairman Ivan Peto said that an agreement between the 
four liberal parties (SZDSZ, Federation of Young Democrats, 
Entrepreneurs' Party, Agrarian Association) means candidates 
will withdraw from the second round in one another's favour in 
13 constituencies. In reply to a question, Peto ruled out talks 
on mutual withdrawals with the MDF. 

</TEXT>

