<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Yugoslavia, Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Police Refuse To Admit Albanian Deportees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serb Police Refuse To Admit Albanian Deportees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0905173494 Tirana ATA in English 1006 GMT 9 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0905173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, May 7 (ATA) -- According to reports, a group 
of 27 Albanians, mainly youngsters expelled from Sweden after 
their requests for political asylum were refused, were not 
allowed to return to Kosova. Police authorities at the Serbian 
border said to the Swedish representatives who were accompanying 
the Albanians that "the group cannot return to Kosova and you 
can do anything you like with them." 
  This act ranks Serbia in the group of countries like Eritrea 
and Ethiopia which do not accept their nationals return to the 
country, the largest Swedish newspaper DAGENS NYHETER writes. 
It also reports that a day after, the group of Albanians were 
sent back to Stockholm and then to some cities in Sweden to stay 
for some days until a reply will be given. 
  According to international convention of 1948, everyone has 
the right to return to his country. But human rights are not of 
any value in countries like Serbia, said Bjorn Gesta Sporong, 
adviser in the Justice Department at the Swedish Foreign 
Ministry. 

</TEXT>

