<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 10 May (MTI) -- If voters allow, the 
national, Christian parties may make back some of their losses 
in the second round of voting on May 29, Laszlo Surjan, chairman 
of the Christian Democratic People's Party (KDNP), said after 
his party's board took two sessions on Monday and Tuesday to 
assess the situation. 
  Surjan could imagine voters either becoming discouraged by 
the second round or realising they still have some political 
leverage. For this reason, the KDNP gives priority to mobilising 
voters and making them aware of their responsibility, he said. 
  KDNP Deputy Chairman Laszlo Varga told MTI that the 
Christian 
Democrats have not yet coordinated second-round cooperation with 
any party. On Tuesday, they held an informal consultation with 
Hungarian Democratic Forum leaders. Varga added that the KDNP 
Executive Committee would decide tomorrow under which terms the 
party would be prepared to make an electoral deal for the second 
round. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

