<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radical Party Proposals on Bosnia Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radical Party Proposals on Bosnia Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005194794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1904 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 10 (TANJUG) -- The opposition Serbian 
Renewal Movement (SPO) on Tuesday assessed that lasting peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina required an immediate halt to all conflicts 
throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina without any ultimatums and any 
promises to any side. President of the SPO Executive Board 
Milan Komnenic told a press conference that the party leader, 
Vuk Draskovic, on Monday familiarized the U.N. Secretary 
General, Butrus Butrus-Ghali, and the foreign ministers of 
Russia, the U.S., Great Britain, France and Greece, with 
proposals to resolve the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  In his letters to these officials, Draskovic pointed out 
that 
after the conflicts have ended, heavy weaponry of all the three 
warring sides (Moslems, Serbs and Croats) should be placed under 
UNPROFOR control -- and when this is over -- complete 
disarmament should be carried out. The leader of the SPO party 
which is the backbone of the Depos coalition, the strongest 
opposition group in the Serbian parliament, suggested in his 
letters the soonest possible holding of a summit of the heads of 
state of Russia, the U.S., France and Great Britain, and the 
chair-country of the European Union, Greece, and the U.N. 
secretary general who would send demands to all the warring 
sides to submit themselves to this summit's decisions. 
  Bosnian Serbs advocate an end be put to all the conflicts 
throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina. This has not been accepted by 
the Bosnian Moslems who propose termination of conflicts on some 
of the battlefronts or a truce of up to two or three months. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

