<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opening of Air Corridor to Belgrade Examined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opening of Air Corridor to Belgrade Examined </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005161694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1527 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 10 (TANJUG) -- The head of the 
Croatian Bureau in Belgrade Zvonimir Markovic said Tuesday [10 
May] that Croatia was interested in the opening of air corridors 
between Belgrade and Zagreb so that planes would not have to fly 
the roundabout way. He told this to the Yugoslav Minister for 
Transport and Communications Blagoje Lucic, the Yugoslav 
Information Ministry reported. 
  The question of the establishment of direct 
telecommunication 
links between Belgrade and Zagreb was also examined during the 
talks as well as the normalisation of road and rail traffic, 
following an agreement with the republic of Serb Krajina (RSK). 
The RSK was declared by the Serbs on their ethnic ancestral 
lands in Croatia in response to Croatia's forcible secession 
from the former Yugoslavia and the downgrading of the Serb 
people to a national minority. 
  The head of the Yugoslav Bureau in Zagreb Veljko Knezevic 
said Monday that the Yugoslav Vice Premier Zeljko Simic and the 
Croatian Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Mate Granic would 
most probably meet at the end of May in Belgrade to discuss the 
possibility of the opening of the Belgrade-Zagreb highway, the 
establishment of rail and telecommonuciations links and the 
linking of Yugoslav and Croatian power systems. 
  All economic and political relations between Yugoslavia 
(Serbia/Montenegro) and Croatia were cut off in 1991 because of 
Zagreb's unilateral forcible secession from the Yugoslav 
Federation. The normalisation of political relations between 
the two countries began in March this year with the opening of 
the Yugoslav and Croatian bureaus in Zagreb and Belgrade 
respectively, which had been agreed in Geneva in January by 
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic and his Croatian 
counterpart Granic. According to the Yugoslav interpretation 
the normalisation of relations between Belgrade and Zagreb in no 
way presupposes a political settlement in the RSK, which should 
be reached bilaterally by the Croatian and Krajina sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-55183 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu091_i_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-091 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Agreement on Maps </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Agreement on Maps </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005225294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2200 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1005225294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The fourth day of the Bosniak-Croatian negotiations 
on implementing the Washington agreement ended late this 
evening. Tihomir Vinkovic reporting for the midnight bulletin of 
Croatian Radio from Vienna: 
  There has still been no agreement on the cantonal maps in 
the 
Bosniak-Croat federation. It seems that stands have been 
harmonized on the hitherto controversial issue of central 
Bosnia. The area is planned to be one whole canton organized on 
the parity principle to reflect the 1991 population census. 
Western Herzegovina is envisaged as a Croat canton and the 
eastern part of Herzegovina will also be organized on the parity 
principle. The negotiations will resume at 1000 on 11 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

