<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic `Expects Nothing' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic `Expects Nothing' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105103794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1000 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As part of the Croat-Bosniak negotiations on 
implementing the Washington agreement, the two delegations have 
resumed talks about border controls in central Bosnia and 
Hercegovina. Bosnian Croat delegation head Kresimir Zubak said 
that there are problems surrounding the issue of the borders and 
that they could be resolved only as part of a package. The 
Muslim side has proposed that Herzegovina be divided into two 
cantons: one Croat and the other with power-sharing on a parity 
basis. On the other hand, the Croatian side insists on a single 
Herzegovina. 
  Muslim delegation head Haris Silajdzic said that he expects 
nothing from today's negotiations in the U.S. Embassy in Vienna. 

</TEXT>

