<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views on Upcoming Assembly Session Examined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Views on Upcoming Assembly Session Examined </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SDS Leader Comments </H4>

<F P=102> AU1005164594 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1005164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There already exists a public admission of this 
cabinet's inability to act, and the quarrels in the 
parliamentary majority aggravate the situation even more. This 
was pointed out by Filip Dimitrov, chairman of the National 
Coordinating Council of the Union of Democratic Forces [SDS], at 
a news conference on 10 May following a meeting of the SDS 
National Coordinating Council. The SDS is not sure that the 
prime minister will really present his plan for personnel and 
structural changes in the cabinet at the 11 May National 
Assembly session, but it hopes that the parliamentary majority 
will express its opinion on the draft decision on the cabinet's 
policy submitted by the SDS deputies. 
  The SDS National Conference will be a closed forum. This 
also 
was decided today by the SDS National Coordinating Council. 

</TEXT>

