<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-091 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations Agree on Federation Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegations Agree on Federation Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105101094 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0800 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1105101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Talks between the Bosniak and Croat delegations 
concerning the implementation of the Constitution of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation are continuing in Vienna today. 
The Vienna talks yesterday centered on the cantons, that is, on 
their territory and borders. No agreement was reached on the 
territory and borders of the cantons in Herzegovina and central 
Bosnia, but new ideas were introduced and these formed the basis 
for the expert teams to propose new solutions. The proposals in 
question propose a smaller number of cantons that would have 
more territory and would contain approximately the same number 
of Bosniaks and Croats. 
  As for the Federal Government, it was agreed in principle 
that it would consist of all together 15 ministries, 11 regular 
ministries and four without portfolio. In addition to the prime 
minister and deputy prime minister, the government would consist 
of 17 members. Five ministries would be headed by Croatian 
ministers, while the rest would go to the Bosniaks, but every 
deputy minister would be from the ranks of the other nationality. 
  It was concluded that it was necessary to reach an overall 
agreement, rather than a partial one. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

