<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Casualties Reported in Inter-Muslim Clashes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Casualties Reported in Inter-Muslim Clashes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205013994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2316 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205013994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, May 11 (TANJUG) -- Many casualties have 
been reported in Wednesday's heavy clashes in western 
Bosnia-Herzegovina between Moslem units loyal to the Moslem 
leadership in Sarajevo and that of the Autonomous Province of 
Western Bosnia (APZB), Moslem-controlled Sarajevo radio reported. 
  The radio, controlled by the authorities loyal to Moslem 
leader Alija Izetbegovic, said that the APZB forces continued 
for a third day in a row their "savage attacks on the Cazin 
border regions, Todorovo and the area of Buzim." The radio 
reported major damage to civilian facilities. 
  The APZB was proclaimed in a referendum of the Moslem 
population in the region in September 1993 and local businessman 
and former Bosnian presidency member Fikret Abdic became its 
president. Abdic, a political opponent to Izetbegovic, has in 
the meantime concluded peace agreements with the Serb Republic, 
the state of the Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

