<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak: `Good Climate' for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pawlak: `Good Climate' for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105135494 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1157 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 11 May--According to Prime Minister Waldemar 
Pawlak, the "strike atmosphere is dying out," which creates a 
good climate for direct talks and for resolving problems. 
  At a meeting with the regional press in Warsaw today, the 
prime minister stated that the government is anxious to preserve 
the basic principle of democracy so that all of the major 
partners-signatories to the enterprise pact would participate in 
talks. That is why the government is attaching importance to 
negotiations within the Tripartite Commission, Pawlak added. 
  Grzegorz Kolodko, deputy prime minister and minister of 
finance, said that the government will not pay for the strikes. 
Asked about their costs, he said they are "too great, 
inadmissible, and unacceptable from a social viewpoint" and 
that, if they were to continue, all of society would shoulder 
the burden. Then it would be difficult to return to the 
previous income tax rates, he added. 
  In Prime Minister Pawlak's view, in accordance with the law, 
compensatory pay for the strikes should be paid by trade unions. 
This has been the case in one of the collieries. "When 
decisions are made, responsibility for their consequences is 
needed," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

